> Bias risks, informed consent, privacy, potential harms, equity implications.
> Does this system reproduce or amplify existing disparities? Who bears the
> consequences when it fails?

[In terms of bias and equity, limited cultural awareness may lead to systematic exclusion of certain ethnic dietary practices. For privacy and data usage, User data (household size, food habits, budget) is sensitive and must be collected with informed consent, stored securely
 maybe in a HIPAA compliant database and not shared with anyone.

For likely potential harms, inaccurate recommendations could lead to nutritional deficiencies, suggest impractical foods (unavailable or culturally inappropriate- foods that the people cannot relate to) and over-reliance on the system may reduce individual autonomy
or critical decision-making

For who is responsible for the tool, 
Failures impact already vulnerable populations (low-income families) so developers and deploying institutions would bear responsibility for monitoring harm, updating the system often and providing support when needed.]

